<TEXT>
canada has reached agreement with 
four provincial governments industry and the united states to go 
ahead with the 366 million radarsat satellite prime minister brian 
mulroney said monday 
mulroney told a conference on science and technology that the 
radarsat program is an ideal illustration of a major step 
forward in canadas space effort 
the radarsat satellite to be launched in 1994 is designed to 
take radar images of the earths surface even in the dark and 
through clouds 
planners have said it will be used to provide information about 
ice conditions in the arctic and to help agricultural and forestry 
industries by detecting the humidity of soil and vegetation 
the radarsat program was announced in september 1987 but 
agreement was delayed because of disputes among the original 
partners canada britain the united states and four canadian 
provinces 
britain withdrew last year and in march ontario reduced its 
proposed contritution saying quebec was getting more than its share 
of work from the project the other participating provinces are 
saskatchewan and british columbia 
the radarsat program originally was to receive the equivalent of 
1736 million in canadian federal funds over a fiveyear period 
mulroney gave no details about the agreement saying they would 
be announced later 
a theme repeated at the conference was that canada does not spend 
enough on research and development and mulroney said much remains 
to be done 
he did not respond to a statement earlier in the day by ontario 
premier david peterson who said canadas investment in research and 
development should be raised to 25 percent of its gross domestic 
product the current level is 136 percent 
mulroney spoke of the responsibility of the private sector in 
financing research 
he said only 3 percent of canadas manufacturing firms have 
internal research and development capabilities and private sector 
support accounts for only 1 percent of the revenue for universities 
compared to seven percent in the united states 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

