<TEXT>
hes just been appointed to a big job in 
washington assistant deputy undersecretary for something he 
figures hell have the presidents ear from time to time be invited 
to state dinners he might call a quick press conference to lay out 
his agenda 
one can almost hear the sound of expectations deflating in this 
anecdote published in a new manual for people new to washington 
i expected a briefing by the white house on what life would be 
like in washington i expected someone to consider my family and say 
hey heres 10 realtors and heres the country club heres the 
schools for your kids and heres some people that would like to meet 
your wife and heres the synopsis from the transition team on how 
to do things 
well i never got any of that it was sink or swim pal 
the teller of that tale is a former government appointee who 
appears along with dozens of others anonymously in a 
survivors guide for government executives subtitled how to 
succeed in washington 
it was written by john h trattner a former journalist and 
diplomat based on interviews with members of the center for 
excellence in government the center is a nonpartisan organization 
of some 400 business leaders who have held appointed policymaking 
or management jobs in government some as far back as the 
administration of franklin d roosevelt 
they were asked for their insights to help those who are about to 
do what they had done move from private life into a high federal 
post 
a repeated theme is that the new appointee would be wise to know 
and use the existing bureaucracy the civil servants who were there 
before him and will be after he leaves 
dont try to do it all the appointee is advised dont be 
afraid to use existing mechanisms build esprit and morale 
remember that staff are there to help you 
much of the advice is common sense but some is eyecatching 
reading it conveys a sense of what it must be like to come to 
washington to work for a president and for a boss one doesnt know 
while leading an unknown staff and having to face congress press 
and constituency with answers right from the start 
here are some samples with backup comments from the 
exgovernment officials drawing on their own experiences 
keep in constant touch with your interest groups an 
exofficials comment one temptation the political appointee has 
to resist is staying in the office and listening only to an 
elite cadre of special assistants youve got to go out youve got 
to have lunch with the lobbying groups even though you dont 
have enough time to get everything done as it is 
youre not being invited in for an ego trip the comment 
be sure you know that the government is very big and your piece 
is going to be only a part of it the president isnt going to wake 
up every day and wonder where you are 
its government by committee get used to it even routine 
decisions in washington are usually drudged over by several 
agencies weeks months even years can go by while a decision 
stumbles through successive phases of research and laborious 
negotiation 
know when not to compromise the quote you have to have 
the patience to hear them out then wait them out then stall them 
out and finally say no the patient intellectually honest stall is 
one of the great government ploys 
control your inbox dont let it control you the quote 
every day i came in there were three inboxes and then there were 
four inboxes and so on so i used to just leave them and if 
something was important enough somebody would eventually come into 
my office and say something like did you get that memo i sent you 
several months ago it was real important we ought to get on that 
and we would 
learn from the professionals the quote there is almost 
always one person whos been around for a long time knows all 
the bodies if you can find that man or woman and befriend them 
and get them to give you the real kind of inside skinny on whats 
going on thats very helpful youve got to find the intelligence 
network inside the system 
no precaution is too small or too troublesome the quote 
for gods sake dont lie to people dont let somebody pay for a 
300 hotel room dont accept gifts dont let people buy you 
lunches 
trattner said it was exhilarating to listen to the former 
officials 
their experience signals the continuing vitality and challenge 
of the political system they embody he said it is a system 
whose uniqueness rests in part on the ability to spur experienced 
and intelligent men and women to place their talents for a time at 
the service of the nation 
