<TEXT>
chinas disdainful response to world criticism 
over its bloody crackdown on student protesters is in keeping with a 
2000year tradition of insularity and a sense of righteousness 
china long assumed a vast gulf between itself called the 
central country in chinese and other countries which were 
considered uncivilized economic selfsufficiency enabled it to 
maintain this view as the limits of communication preserved 
ignorance about the rest of the world 
but china no longer is selfsufficient and foreign opinion cannot 
be blocked out 
foreign investment and technology are key to its economic 
development plans and china has come to rely on some imports even 
while denouncing the united states for sheltering a leading 
dissident in its beijing embassy china imported extra tons of us 
wheat to make up for its own poor harvest 
since senior leader deng xiaoping began economic reforms a decade 
ago nearly 10000 foreign companies have set up joint ventures in 
china with a total investment of 12 billion many manufacture goods 
for export generating hard currency china needs for its 
modernization 
chinese leaders have said repeatedly since the army attacked 
unarmed protesters in bejing on june 34 killing hundreds that 
they want and expect foreign countries to continue trade and 
investment but they also have reiterated they will not accept 
foreign criticism of the bloody crackdown 
we hope that all countries that wish to keep and develop 
friendly relations with china will take a longterm view and avoid 
doing anything to hurt the feelings of the chinese people premier 
li peng told top party officials in a recent speech 
government spokesman yuan mu was blunter telling a news 
conference we are not spineless people we are not afraid 
of condemnation or sanction 
it has gotten both the united states cut off military sales and 
contacts france and the netherlands froze relations japan chinas 
largest singlecountry source of aid put off new development 
assistance loans canada and france temporarily withdrew their 
ambassadors 
several countries canceled planned highlevel official exchanges 
it is not the first time foreign governments have criticized 
dengs policies the us congress has passed repeated resolutions 
criticizing china for opening fire on proindependence protesters in 
tibet over the past two years 
however it is the first time condemnation of china has been so 
nearly universal even hungarys communist government expressed 
outrage and the soviet parliament urged wisdom reason and a 
weighted approach 
it also is the first time that criticism has been backed by 
action 
a speech deng gave in 1987 indicates he may not have expected 
that he said that after the last largescale arrests of 
prodemocracy activists in 1979 china suffered no discredit 
on the contrary the prestige of the country is steadily 
growing he said 
china also has emerged unscathed from controversies over its 
foreign policy such as its arms sales to iran and support in 
cambodia of the khmer rouge whose forces killed hundreds of 
thousands of countrymen while in power from 197578 
the decision of the top government spokesman yuan mu to give a 
rare interview to the us television network nbc last week may have 
been an effort to counter the avalanche of foreign condemnation 
in it he reiterated the governments position that the army 
fired on the crowds june 34 only after provocation he condemned 
foreign news reports as distortions and suggested that even foreign 
film of the killing was fabricated 
china could have avoided much of the bad press abroad if it had 
expelled all foreign reporters ahead of time but thousands of 
foreign businessmen and diplomats who also could bear witness would 
have had to be expelled as well 
whats more such a move would have been an admission that china 
had something to hide chinese officials apparently believe that if 
they reiterate the official explanation often enough and wait long 
enough foreign businessmen and diplomats will trickle back 
they may be right a survey of 116 american business executives 
before the crackdown found 55 percent believed china would become a 
more attractive market after the shooting 67 executives were asked 
again fiftythree percent still agreed 
</TEXT>
