when pacific southwest airlines flight 1771 
took off from los angeles its passengers included a nononsense 
supervisor and a hottempered former underling who sneaked a gun 
aboard 
over central california the bad feelings between david burke and 
his former usair boss ray thomson ended in an airborne shooting 
that moved from the passenger compartment to the cockpit 
with its slain crew slumped over the controls midway to their san 
francisco destination dec 7 1987 the fourengine bae146 smashed 
into a hillside north of san luis obispo all 43 aboard were killed 
eighteen months later attorneys are dissecting the final minutes 
of the life of burke 35 the usair employee was fired three weeks 
earlier by thomson 48 who had denied burke reinstatement during a 
meeting shortly before they boarded the flight 
the negligence lawsuit is midway through trial in superior court 
it was filed by the relatives of eight passengers and two crew 
members against the los angeles department of airports ogden allied 
security co psa and usair which bought psa 
jurors will have to fix percentages of responsibility if any 
for the defendants as well as any damages which attorneys agree 
could run into millions of dollars no set dollar amount was 
requested 
at issue is whether the defendants could have reasonably guessed 
burkes actions and stopped him the defendants have said that was 
impossible and have countersued the estate of burke as the man 
solely responsible for the crash 
