a california woman facing criminal charges in 
her daughters death because she tried to heal the child through 
prayer rather than seeking medical help lost a supreme court appeal 
today 
the justices without comment refused to block the womans trial 
in sacramento on charges of childendangerment and involuntary 
manslaughter 
the high court has turned away similar appeals previously 
laurie walker a christian scientist chose to treat with prayer 
rather than medical attention her 4yearold daughter shauntay 
when the girl became ill with flulike symptoms on feb 21 1984 
and four days later developed a stiff neck 
ms walker contacted an accredited prayer practitioner from her 
church and a christian science nurse to attend the child but 
shauntay nevertheless lost weight and grew disoriented 
the young girl died march 9 of meningitis 
californias childneglect law does not allow prosecution of 
parents who provide prayer rather than medical care for their 
children but prosecutors charged ms walker with childendangerment 
and involuntary manslaughter if convicted she could receive a 
maximum sentence of six years in prison 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for ms walker contended 
that the conflicting state laws result in a denial of fair 
warning for christian scientists 
referring to mixed signals or deliberate ambiguity in the 
criminal law the appeal said such prosecutions amount to trials 
of faith forbidden by the constitution 
the california supreme court last nov 10 rejected arguments that 
forcing ms walker to stand trial would violate her religious 
freedom 
an adequately effective and less restrictive alternative is not 
available to further the states compelling interest in assuring the 
provision of medical care to gravely ill children whose parents 
refuse such treatment on religious grounds the state court said 
the first amendment protecting religious freedom and its 
california equivalent do not bar defendants criminal prosecution 
it said 
but the state court added whether this defendants particular 
conduct was sufficiently culpable to justify conviction of 
involuntary manslaughter and felony child endangerment remains a 
question in the exclusive province of the jury 
the case is walker vs superior court 881471 
