<TEXT>
the supreme court today barred asbestos 
manufacturers from suing the government to recover money they paid 
to a navy shipyard worker injured by inhaling the product 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by two 
manufacturers in a case from washington state 
albert lopez worked as a pipe fitter pipe coverer and insulator 
at the puget sound naval shipyard in washington from 1947 to 1984 
eaglepicher industries inc settled a claim against it by paying 
lopez 10000 raymark industries inc did the same for 7200 
both manufacturers supplied asbestos to the navy to insulate 
ships 
lopezs claims were used in the lower courts as a test case of 
the governments liability for injuries suffered by shipyard workers 
a federal appeals court here ruled last september that the 
manufacturers lack any legal basis to recover from the government 
the money they pay to settle asbestosrelated claims against them 
the appeals court rejected arguments that the government by 
ordering asbestos in effect insured the manufacturers against 
lawsuits by injured workers 
the appeals court said the manufacturers seem to be suggesting 
that the government knew more about the hazards of asbestos than 
it ever disclosed to its suppliers 
the manufacturers appear to be arguing that if they knew of the 
dangers they would have gone out of the asbestos business at once 
and saved themselves untold liability or else would have purchased 
all the insurance available and passed the cost on in sharply 
higher prices the appeals court said 
we may have to suppress our wonderment that anyone would have 
known more about the hazards of asbestos than those responsible 
companies who used it as raw material the court continued 
but it added even if the government knew more about the dangers 
of asbestos than the manufacturers there still is no legal basis 
for the companies to recover the money 
the bush administration urged the justices to reject the 
companies appeal 
justice department lawyers noted that the high court ruled last 
year that defense contractors are immune from personalinjury 
lawsuits when they follow government specifications and warn the 
government of any dangers of which they are aware 
but that ruling does not shield manufacturers of products found 
to cause injury independent of government specifications for their 
use the government lawyers said 
the cases are eaglepicher vs us 881382 and raymark vs 
us 881418 
