<TEXT>
margaret randall a professor and writer 
threatened with deportation from the united states for supporting 
communism lost a supreme court appeal today 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that it is 
premature to consider the constitutional and legal issues she raised 
her appeal is supported by a number of prominent writers 
including norman mailer arthur miller toni morrison william 
styron and kurt vonnegut 
ms randall lost her us citizenship after leaving this country 
in 1961 she lived in mexico cuba and nicaragua writing about 
social change and revolution in third world nations 
she returned to this country on a visitors visa in 1984 and has 
been living in albuquerque nm near her elderly parents while 
teaching at the university of new mexico 
ms randall applied for permanent resident status in 1984 a step 
toward regaining her us citizenship but the application was 
rejected by an official of the immigration and naturalization 
service in el paso texas 
the official based the rejection on ms randalls association 
with and her activities and writing in support of the 
communistdominated governments of cuba north vietnam and 
nicaragua the official said those activities and writings go 
far beyond mere dissent 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled last year that it is 
premature for the federal courts to consider the merits of ms 
randalls case 
the appeals court said it is likely she never will be deported 
and because of a change in federal law it appears she eventually 
will be allowed to regain her citizenship 
the appeals court noted that a move to block her deportation is 
pending before the us board of immigration appeals 
the appeals court also pointed out that congress in 1988 
generally made it illegal to deny a visa or an application for 
permanent resident status to anyone based on their beliefs 
statements or associations 
it therefore appears that the larger question initially raised 
whether margaret randall could regain united states citizenship 
is now reduced to the question when can she regain it the 
appeals court said 
her lawyers argued that postponing her opportunity to regain 
citizenship is causing her serious harm 
the case is randall vs thornburgh 881412 
</TEXT>
