<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled unanimously today that 
federal courts have authority to referee some disputes over electric 
power rates between public utilities and local or state regulatory 
agencies 
the justices ordered a federal court to review a claim by new 
orleans public service inc nopsi a utility seeking to pass on 
135 million in costs to its customers 
justice antonin scalia in his opinion for the high court 
compared the utilitys claim to a challenge to an allegedly 
unconstitutional state law or local zoning ordinance 
we would assuredly not require such suits to be brought in 
state courts he said moreover he said there is no doctrine 
that the availability or even the pendency of state judicial 
proceedings excludes the federal courts from ruling in such cases 
the justices in a related ruling last year severely limited the 
authority of states to lower electric rates public utilities charge 
as a result of agreements with federal regulators 
but that decision left unanswered whether federal judges should 
rule in such disputes or should leave these matters to state courts 
the court said today that federal judges should not abstain 
todays case involves a nearly decadeold dispute between nopsi 
and the new orleans city council which under louisiana law sets 
utility rates charged consumers in new orleans 
the council barred the utility from charging customers for the 
costs the utility incurred by buying electric power generated by the 
36 billion grand gulf 1 nuclear power plant in port gibson miss 
the rates charged the new orleans utility to purchase power from 
grand gulf were set by the federal energy regulatory commission 
therefore the utility argued city and state officials are 
powerless to prevent it from passing on the costs to its customers 
the federal energy regulatory commission in 1985 ordered the new 
orleans utility to pay 17 percent of the cost of constructing grand 
gulf 1 
nopsi in a partial settlement with the city council in 1986 
agreed to absorb 512 million of the costs of grand gulf 
the utility said the city had assured it would be allowed to 
recover the remaining 135 million share of its costss through 
higher retail rates over a period of time 
but the council said the utility acted imprudently in failing to 
resell the power it agreed to purchase from grand gulf and the 
council blocked a passthrough to the customers 
the utility sued in federal court for permission to pass on the 
135 million to its customers arguing that the federal commissions 
role in the matter preempted the city councils power 
a federal judge denied the utilitys claims and the 5th us 
circuit court of appeals upheld the judges ruling 
the case is new orleans public service vs new orleans city 
council 88348 
</TEXT>
