<TEXT>
the supreme court today reinstated the life 
sentence of a convicted missouri murderer ruling that a lower court 
wrongly decided he should go free 
by a 54 vote the court said the constitutions doublejeopardy 
protections for criminal defendants did not require that larry p 
thomas life sentence be thrown out 
neither the doublejeopardy clause nor any other constitutional 
provision exists to provide unjustified windfalls justice anthony 
m kennedy wrote for the court 
thomas was convicted of murder and attempted robbery in the 
botched holdup of an automobile parts store in st louis on nov 8 
1972 
mentoe vernell a customer was killed in a shootout 
thomas was sentenced to 15 years in prison for attempted robbery 
and to life for murder 
former gov christopher bond commuted the robbery sentence in 
1981 after thomas had served about eight years he remained in 
prison on the murder conviction 
a state court subsequently threw out the sentence for attempted 
robbery and credited the time thomas had served for that crime to 
the murder sentence 
but the 8th us circuit court of appeals ruled last year that 
the multiple sentences for the same crime violated thomas 
doublejeopardy protections since the governors commutation meant 
that thomas legally had served one of his sentences the other 
sentence had to be thrown out and thomas set free the appeals court 
said 
but the nations highest court disagreed today 
the missouri courts alteration of thomas sentence to a single 
term for felony murder with credit for time served provided suitable 
protection for his doublejeopardy rights kennedy wrote 
he was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white harry a blackmun and sandra day oconnor 
justices antonin scalia william j brennan thurgood marshall 
and john paul stevens dissented 
writing for the four scalia said the court wrongly was making an 
exception from its previous doublejeopardy rulings to avoid what it 
perceives as an unjust result 
a technical rule with equitable exceptions is no rule at all 
scalia said three strikes out the state broke the rules here 
and must abide by the result 
the case is jones vs thomas 88420 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

