<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether union members who sue their union for allegedly denying fair 
representation are entitled to a jury trial if they also seek 
monetary compensation such as back pay 
lawsuits accusing unions of breaching their duty of fair 
representation generally are tried before judges without juries 
but ruling in a case from north carolina last year the 4th us 
circuit court of appeals said a jury trial can be demanded when 
monetary compensation is part of the relief sought 
other appeals courts have ruled differently 
the 4th circuit courts ruling was a victory for 27 truck drivers 
who sued local 391 of the teamsters union in 1983 
the suit stemmed from the drivers transfers from various 
locations to the mclean trucking cos terminal in winstonsalem 
nc 
after the transfers the 27 were laid off and recalled on several 
occasions 
the drivers contend that mclean breached a collectivebargaining 
agreement by manipulating recall procedures so it could give other 
drivers preference over them and that local 391 failed to fairly 
represent them in the resulting grievances 
the suit sought among other things compensatory damages for 
lost wages and benefits 
the case is local 391 vs terry 881719 
</TEXT>
