<TEXT>
the navy in a letter released monday pulled 
back from a critical assessment of a cruisemissile engine agreement 
with williams international saying the deal has resulted in lower 
prices 
in 1978 williams of walled lake mich signed an agreement 
that would allow a competitor teledyne industries inc to use 
williams technology to build cruisemissile engines for the navy 
in return the navy guaranteed it would buy 240 engines a year from 
williams plus 25 percent of any additional purchases up to 1200 
engines annually 
the navy intends to cancel the agreement on grounds that it 
commits the service to future contracts in a way inconsistent with 
procurement laws 
for each of the past 10 years williams has submitted 
competitive prices well below those of its competitor for production 
engines navy secretary h lawrence garrett iii wrote last week in 
a letter to sen carl levin dmich we do believe that the fact 
of competition has benefited the taxpayer by creating an added 
incentive to lower prices 
the letter represented a sharp departure from a letter garrett 
then undersecretary of the navy wrote to levin in april 
then garrett said the agreement with williams was severely 
limiting our contracting options and decision in a manner which we 
believe inconsistent with sound procurement policy and the public 
interest 
in the april letter garrett also said teledynes prices had 
become very competitive with williams beginning last year 
the april letter was leaked by a whistleblower group called the 
project on military procurement levin released last weeks letter 
garrett said the navy still intends to cancel the 1978 agreement 
but said that intention in no way implies criticism of williams 
internationals integrity or performance 
we appreciate the emphasis on ethics that has always been part 
of williams internationals management and we consider it an 
outstanding navy contractor garrett wrote williams has exceeded 
its reliability goals and delivered every engine ahead of the 
contract date 
the associated press sought an explanation from the navy of the 
differences in the two letters lt bruce cole a navy spokesman 
said monday he couldnt comment until he had looked into the matter 
there are some real differences there levin said of the two 
letters maybe he recognizes that his first letter was really not 
the most accurate reflection of the situation 
i havent talked to them nor has my staff levin said 
