<TEXT>
more than 700 educational institutions could 
lose student financial aid funds because they have failed to meet 
new requirements involving drugs and eligibility for aid the 
education department said monday 
in order for their students to receive certain grants and loans 
schools must now certify that they are drugfree workplaces for 
their lowincome students to receive pell grants they also must 
certify that they do not employ anyone who has been barred from 
receiving money from any federal agency 
the department said 700 schools will not receive their 19891990 
pell grants which the schools disburse to students for tuition 
books and other academic uses if they do not file both 
certifications 
another 180 schools face delay or loss of 19891990 funds for 
campusbased grants loans and workstudy programs if they dont 
submit drugfree workplace forms 
the pell grant suspension and debarment forms were due on june 16 
and the drugfree certifications are due on june 22 the money is 
scheduled for release on july 1 
education secretary lauro cavazos said the number of schools that 
have failed so far to file the necessary certifications amounts to 
nearly 10 percent of all institutions participating in federal 
financial aid programs he said the department has written and 
telephoned all affected institutions in some cases as many as four 
times 
these schools failure to comply with these mandatory 
certifications could have a devastating impact on thousands of 
students nationwide who rely on federal financial aid for 
postsecondary education cavazos said in a statement 
the drugfree workplace certification is part of a 1988 law that 
requires all federal grant recipients and most contractors to 
certify that they have a drugfree work environment the law 
requires specific steps such as notifying employees in writing that 
drug abuse in the workplace is banned and educating employees to the 
dangers of drug abuse and the availability of counseling 
the suspension and debarment certification for pell grants is 
part of a governmentwide regulation designed to make sure that if 
someone has been barred from receiving money from one federal 
agency he or she isnt eligible for federal dollars from another 
agency the same type of certification will be required for the 
campusbased loan grant and workstudy programs next year a 
department official said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

