<TEXT>
a production dispute has forced the federal 
aviation administration to put on hold its plan for bringing a new 
generation of landing systems to the nations airports 
the faa installed its first microwave landing system at lebanon 
airport in a highly publicized ceremony april 6 and the laconia and 
manchester airports were scheduled to get the stateoftheart 
system by late summer 
however earlier this month the faa took a step toward 
terminating its contract with hazeltine corp its prime contractor 
for the system faa spokesman john leyden said late last week 
as the agency looks to other electronics firms for the new 
technology it must sell the new system to reluctant air carriers 
who say it isnt much better than the instrument landing system now 
in use 
leyden said the faa remains committed to an international 
agreement to make the microwave system standard at airports 
worldwide by 1998 and has not changed plans to equip all us 
airports with the new system by the year 2000 
the system which uses highfrequency microwaves to direct planes 
to landings is virtually immune to weather it allows planes to 
make curved and steeper approaches which increases an airports 
flight capacity and helps planes avoid residential areas 
the faa contracted with hazeltine in 1984 for 178 systems at 79 
million but the commack nybased firm said the price was too 
low and entered an unauthorized workslowdown last august said 
dick arnold head of the faas microwave landing system program 
after nearly six months of fruitless negotiations the faa on 
june 2 sent hazeltine a letter saying the companys actions could 
lead to termination of the contract hazeltine has until thursday to 
respond 
hazeltine officials were phoned for comment but refused to say 
anything about the issue 
leyden said cancelling the hazeltine contract wont mean 
scrapping the faas installation program he said the agency plans 
to buy 26 systems from other sources 
but the cancellation will lead to further delays in the 
installation program jerry casavant the faas associate program 
director for the microwave landing system in new england said it 
already was at least 3 years behind the original schedule 
leyden said that with installations at laconia and manchester put 
on hold the faa is considering redirecting early installations to 
more highprofile highvolume airports such as kennedy 
international in new york city 
the three new hampshire airports would have been part of the 
first phase of planned us installations which included bostons 
logan airport and kennedy international 
the idea was to equip an entire hubandspoke network so that the 
airlines that serve those airports would see the benefit of 
equipping their planes with the expensive receiving systems 
the second phase of the faas plan if approved by congress is 
for 750 systems that would mean complete replacement of the more 
than 700 instrument landing systems in use in the nations airports 
as well as installation of microwave systems at sites unsuitable for 
the old system 
