<DOCNO> AP890619-0183 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
private employers cannot unilaterally begin 
testing union workers for drug and alcohol use but can test job 
applicants regardless of whether unions object the national labor 
relations board said monday in its first decisions on the 
controversial issue 
the board however said that if employers test applicants for 
drug and alcohol use they cannot deny unions information about those 
who are offered jobs but do not accept them including those who 
refuse to submit to tests 
in rejecting attempts by employers to unlilaterally implement 
drug and alcohol testing of current workers represented by unions 
the board said testing is an issue that falls under collective 
bargaining and therefore must be the subject of unionmanagement 
negotiations 
but the board said there is no such protection for job applicants 
and said employers do not need to negotiate with their unions if 
they want to subject applicants to drug and alcohol testing 
that decision long awaited by employers and business groups 
could result in a proliferation of applicanttesting policies 
attorneys familiar with labor law said monday 
the precedentsetting nlrb decisions came the same day the 
supreme court ruled that railroads may require tests for workers 
without bargaining with unions over the issue railway and airline 
workers are covered under the railway labor act not the national 
labor relations act that the nlrb is empowered to enforce 
attorneys and union officials familiar with drug testing cases 
said the supreme court decisions would have limited impact outside 
the rail and airline industries where drug testing is common 
particularly in positions with direct impact on public safety but 
they predicted the issues in the cases decided by the nlrb on monday 
could ultimately end up before the high court 
in the first case involving the johnsonbateman co of etiwanda 
calif the nlrb said the company violated its collective bargaining 
agreement with the machinists union when it in december 1986 
informed employees that it would require drug and alcohol tests for 
any employee injured at work 
we conclude that drug and alcohol testing of employees who 
require treatment for injuries received while on the job is a 
mandatory subject of bargaining the board said 
the board ordered the company to negotiate with the union if it 
wanted to adopt such a testing policy for its unionrepresented 
production and maintenance employees 
attempts to reach company officials for comment were not 
immediately successful a receptionist said none of the company 
owners was in the office and the lawyer who represented the company 
also was not at his office monday afternoon 
in the second case the board reversed an administrative law 
judges decision that preemployment drug and alcohol testing by the 
star tribune of minneapolis was an issue the newspaper needed to 
negotiate with its union 
we find that drug and alcohol testing of applicants for 
employment is not a mandatory subject of bargaining the board 
said 
john dennison the newspapers vice president for labor 
relations said the star tribune was gratified by the decision 
dennison said the newspaper has received numerous inquiries about 
the status of its case and speculated that people who had been 
taking a sit back and wait approach may now go ahead with 
applicanttesting policies 
the board did say the newspaper violated the national labor 
relations act by refusing to furnish the union with the requested 
information relating to the drug and alcohol testing of prospective 
employees 
the board said the union the newspaper guild was entitled to 
the information to monitor star tribune hiring practices for any 
signs of discrimination 
the union as part of its challenge of the policy said male 
applicants were allowed to provide urine samples without being 
observed while female applicants were required to give the samples 
partially unclothed and in the presence of a nurse 
the nlrb ordered the newspaper to provide the guild with the 
names addresses and telephone numbers of all applicants to which it 
conditionally offered employment in guildrepresented positions 
since january 1987 and to identify all those in that group who 
refused to submit to drug and alcohol screening 
the nlrb adopting reasonining similar to its decision in the 
johnsonbatemen case upheld the judges 1988 ruling that the 
newspaper violated its collective bargaining agreement with the 
guild by trying to unilaterally implement a drug testing policy for 
current workers in january 1987 
dennison said the newspaper had not enforced the policy and that 
the issue was the subject of current negotiations with the guild 
</TEXT>
