<TEXT>
the united states proposed monday that free 
elections be adopted by all 35 member nations of the conference on 
security and cooperation in europe 
by introducing this proposal we are setting down a marker we 
are establishing a goal which we believe should be pursued 
vigorously said congressman steny h hoyer dmd cochairman of 
the us commission on security and cooperation in europe 
he said the proposal challenges those participating states who 
do not yet permit free elections to give their citizens the right to 
freely participate in their own government 
he spoke at the monthlong conference on the human dimension 
which closes friday 
over the past three weeks the delegations meeting mainly in 
closed sessions have been calling to account nations accused of 
human rights violations romania and bulgaria have been frequent 
targets 
the fingerpointing technique is part of a process agreed to at a 
meeting in january in vienna of the conference on security and 
cooperation in europe 
the united states and canada and all european countries except 
albania are members of csce 
the us proposal also calls for allowing citizens to establish 
political parties and organizations permitting individuals to seek 
positions of public service and having elections observed by outside 
governments institutions or organizations 
the yearning for democracy throughout the world is a fact 
that is unstoppable hoyer told a news conference 
he acknowledged that obtaining the needed consensus to adopt the 
proposal was unlikely tomorrow but said we believe that the 
winds of change for democracy are very very powerful 
morris b abram head of the us delegation said that in the 
united states the flow of moral authority is from the people up 
and with the freeelection proposal we are demonstrating that the 
crux of the whole human rights movement rests on that principle 
the paris conference is the first of three csce human rights 
meeting to be held in line with the 1975 helsinki accords next 
years conference is to be in copenhagen and the third is scheduled 
for moscow in 1991 
