<TEXT>
vietnam cambodia and laos are beckoning 
foreign tourists to their temples beaches and battlefields in hopes 
of accumulating dollars and other hard currencies to strengthen 
their ailing economies 
recent reforms have greatly loosened travel to and within the 
three communistgoverned nations long sealed off by wars and 
suspicious officialdom 
some us war veterans have returned to vietnam in recent years 
to visit battlefields where they fought the viet cong and north 
vietnamese and vietnam would like to see more of the 27 million 
who served return but us sanctions might prevent that 
west europeans are going to angkor cambodias ancient capital 
and tour groups are flying to the former royal capital of luang 
prabang in laos 
the potential is tremendous said hp tuggener who operates 
a travel agency in bangkok thailand the demand will be far 
greater than they can absorb in the next few years its been closed 
for so long there are thousands just waiting to get in 
tuggener who has been involved in indochina tourism for several 
decades said in bangkok that shortages of hotels aircraft tour 
guides and other services will hold back largescale tourism hanoi 
for example currently has 671 hotel beds compared to 24000 in hong 
kong and 25600 in bangkok thailands capital 
our policy now is to be more open to receive more guests 
said tourism official nguyen cuong hien but i can tell you 
vietnam as a tourist destination is virgin land 
vietnam and cambodia come under the us trading with the enemy 
act which means americans can go to those two countries but cannot 
spend money there the intent is to keep us dollars from flowing 
into the economies of countries still considered enemies laos is 
not affected since the united states never broke relations with it 
the us treasury department last year also made it illegal for 
americans to arrange promote or facilitate group or individual 
tours or travel to any country listed under the trading with the 
enemy act others on the list are cuba and north korea 
under its new regulations the treasury department has said it 
intended to prosecute two veterans donald mills and john myers of 
akron ohio members of the vietnam veterans of america who have 
organized six tours for veterans since 1984 in a program to heal 
old deep wounds the american civil liberties union maintains 
treasurys regulations violate the veterans first amendment rights 
and says it will defend them if they are prosecuted 
on june 14 a us federal court in bridgeport conn penalized 
lindblad travel inc of westport conn a total of 75000 for 
offering tours to vietnam and cambodia 
exempt from the us sanctions are journalists scholars or 
others who have a professional interest in the two countries 
in 1988 some 42000 travelers came to indochina in contrast to 
neighboring thailands 42 million but projections are all upward 
with vietnam expecting 100000 largely capitalist tourists by 
1990 compared with 40000 last year tourist visas which once took 
up to three months to get are generally in hand within a week 
among the poorest in the world the indochinese nations hope 
tourist income will help revive their economies hard currency fever 
is spreading rapidly 
dollars dollars chanted a taxi driver at hanoi airport 
unable to come up with any other english words at angkor cambodian 
officials are charging some of the highest entrance fees in the 
world 120 to get into two major temples transportation food and 
tourguide fees are extra 
vietnam hien said earned 57 million from tourism last year 
but it received about 60 applications from 17 countries for 
investment in the tourism sector 
hien said a west german company will build a 14story hotel in 
hanoi while a frenchindonesian group is set to overhaul the thong 
nhat an atmospheric but quickly fading relic of french colonial 
days others are eyeing vietnams often stunning 1860mile 
coastline and ho chi minh city the dynamic southern economic hub 
once called saigon 
hien who heads a department in the national tourism agency 
stressed that standards of service also had to be radically 
improved there are plans to send tourism employees to the west for 
training while the countrys foreign investment code allows foreign 
management of hotels 
cambodias top draw is angkor a complex of magnificent temples 
dating to the 9th century there are four other official tourist 
destinations but a continuing guerrilla war puts large areas of the 
country offlimits only 1500 tourists came last year but just a 
few years ago there were none 
with prospects for a peace settlement talks have been initiated 
for air links between phnom penh the capital and points like 
bangkok tokyo and hong kong phnom penhs hotels are being 
refurbished including the elegant cambodiana on the tonle sap 
river which is slated to have 200 of its 388 rooms ready by the end 
of the year 
although fewer than 600 tourists visited laos in the first six 
months of this year the easy overland access from thailand gives 
it a decided advantage 
travel agencies are offering group packages such as a sixday 
590aperson tour that includes stays in the capital vientiane 
and luang prabang a templestudded retreat nestled in a valley of 
the mekong river 
