<TEXT>
ecologists and farmers in portugal and 
spain are at war against spreading eucalyptus trees the enemy is a 
paper pulp industry that encourages planting more and more of them 
eucalyptus plantations are sprouting up rapidly in the two 
countries as the industry seeks a secure supply of the raw material 
it will need to meet the demand for paper as the european economic 
community lowers trade barriers in 1992 
but farmers and ecologists claim eucalyptus trees drink up too 
much water from the soil endangering traditional olive trees 
chestnut trees and other nutbearing trees they also maintain the 
trees cause land erosion that kills off undergrowth vital to the 
survival of brown bears and other wildlife 
cellulose producers dispute claims the trees are harmful they 
say eucalyptus trees grow fast and are ideally suited to iberian 
soil and climate and that plantations will provide more export 
revenue and create jobs 
the arguments are passionate and tempers run high in march 
protestors in the portuguese town of valpacos clashed with police 
when farmers tried to rip up eucalyptus seedlings from a 396acre 
private plantation 
the region is portugals poorest 
we stopped them planting more eucalyptus at valpacos said 
olive grower joao silva if they try anywhere else well do 
the same again but worse 
if they want to plant eucalyptus they should plant where 
theres plenty water here we dont even have enough to drink 
environmentalists claim the eucalyptus first brought from 
australia in the late 1800s can turn fertile land into desert 
the eucalyptus consumes more water than almost any other tree 
and impedes other plants from growing nearby said santiago martin 
barajas vice president of the federation of spanish wildlife 
protection groups 
portugals interior already poor is being turned into a giant 
eucalyptus plantation and more people are moving toward the coast 
leaving villages deserted said serafim riem a spokesman for 
portuguese ecology group quercus 
the european economic community which faces a paper shortage 
imports 195 billion worth of wood annually 
timber and pulp command high prices and this encourages 
landowners to plant eucalyptus which can be 12 years about half 
the time of more traditional trees 
eucalyptus for us is green crude oil said luis mira amaral 
industry and energy minister for portugal where wood pulp paper 
and cellulose account for 8 percent of yearly export earnings 
spanish environmentalists fear the eec will subsidize massive 
eucalyptus plantings in northern spain where the mix of atlantic 
and mediterranean climates favors growth 
portuguese landowners already tap eec funds via the governments 
forestry action program paf while assistance to traditional tree 
planters is higher paf pays up to 30 percent of project costs for 
smallscale eucalyptus plantations 
portugal has no other vocation said eliseu baena forestry 
director at caima one of portugals big four cellulose producers 
if landowners want to restore their lands theyre going to do 
it with a profitable crop 
baena added that portugal doesnt make full use of its 104 
million acres of highgrade farmland so theres no reason not to 
use lowerquality land for cashcrops like eucalyptus 
he acknowledges that eucalyptus trees should be planted away from 
springs or rivers but refutes ecologists claims that they erode 
soil or kill off undergrowth vital to wildlife 
antonio navas deputy director of spains institute for wildlife 
preservation icona suggests the environmentalists might be poorly 
informed 
there hasnt been a clear debate he said the eucalyptus 
is blamed for causing diseases for being malignant 
said baena i think as much as half of portugals land could be 
forested and 30 percent of that could be planted with eucalyptus 
according to lisbons general directorate for forestry 
eucalyptus trees make up only 113 percent of portugals forests or 
about 4 percent of the countrys total land area of 35600 square 
miles 
but portugal is planting more eucalyptus than any other tree it 
accounts for 75 percent of all paf projects approved since may 
1988 or under consideration 
spain officially registers 495000 acres of eucalyptus but navas 
said the actual total is probably double that 
rui tadeu a teacherfarmer in trasosmontes in the valpacos 
region says landowners dont need eucalyptus to make money 
he produces nuts honey and port wine which bring a high return 
and plans to convert a derelict farm building into a hunting and 
tourist lodge 
the pulp producers promise more jobs from eucalyptus but most 
of the process is mechanized so the jobs are few and mainly in 
factories away from the country he said 
