<TEXT>
here is a survey that threatens to undermine one 
of the most popular and cherished notions of real estate analysts 
that the percentage of firsttime homebuyers shrinks as interest 
rates and prices rise 
the notion has been so readily accepted in recent years that it 
has become esteemed as theory just one step from becoming law 
common sense seemed to support it and still seems to 
doesnt it make sense to expect firsttimers to drop out when the 
average price of a starter house rises to 77800 from 63000 and 
when interest rates fluctuate between 93 percent and 124 percent 
those changes actually occurred between the beginning of 1985 and 
march 1989 the period under study 
but an analysis of more than 150000 sales in the past five years 
now shows the percentage of firsttime buyers remained steady 
throughout the period at about 40 percent of the total regardless 
of interest rates or price jiggles 
such a finding would seem to defy one of the basic laws of 
economics 
in spite of the law monte helme vice president of century 21 
real estate corp declares there is no direct correlation between 
interest rates and home prices and the activity level of firsttime 
homebuyers 
the apparent explanation for the seeming contradiction he 
suggests is that as costs rise the average firsttime buyer is a 
few years older tends to buy a smaller house or condo and may buy 
in less expensive neighborhoods 
in short the type of firsttime buyer changes the product 
purchased changes the total number of sales might change and the 
place of purchase might too 
but according to the study of 150000 century 21 real estate 
sales throughout the country the 40 percent ratio remains almost 
fixed 
however that finding even if true doesnt mean firsttime 
buyers are unaffected by rising rates and prices obviously they 
are the study suggests for instance that some of the younger 
buyers are knocked out of the market 
but curiously the percentages of all firsttime homebuyers 
varied little in the century 21 study ranging from a low of 392 
percent in 1988 to a high of 403 percent in 1986 through the first 
quarter of 1989 the rate was 394 percent 
the findings do tend to support a contention of some active real 
estate people that homebuyers are far more flexibile and adaptive 
than they are credited with being 
a better understanding of markets may have reduced somewhat the 
perception of risk involved in homebuying new buyers for example 
recognize that their interest costs could fall rather than remain 
fixed at high levels 
in addition todays firsttime buyers have foresaken the idea of 
moving immediately into the house of their dreams evidence can be 
found in almost every city in america that young families are 
willing to lower their sights move into lesser neighborhoods and 
apply their own labor in order to raise values 
whatever judgment is finally made of the findings there is 
enough evidence already to warn economists and others from making 
the almost instant conclusion that firsttime buyers are wiped out 
by rising rates and prices 
</TEXT>
