<TEXT>
when gis came home after world war ii 
the nation looked to the great forests of the northwest for lumber 
to build their houses 
oregon and washington mills responded and still supply more than 
a third of the lumber and plywood used in the united states 
there was always that one more shining hill covered with trees 
to the west said us forest service budget officer ron johnson 
in portland now we find theres a pacific ocean and we fell into 
it 
from the western slope of the cascade range to the shore of the 
pacific this is the home of the douglas fir the towering king of 
the ancient forests whose structural strength tops all other lumber 
it is also home to the northern spotted owl a 14inch bird that 
could face extinction because with rare exceptions it wont nest 
or hunt anywhere but the dwindling virgin forests that are most 
prized for timber 
while logs are tied up in the legal battle over how much of the 
national forests can be cut without killing off the spotted owl 
record amounts of raw timber grown on private and state land are 
being shipped for premium prices to japan china and korea without 
ever seeing the inside of an american mill 
if a log is of export quality and is available to be exported 
it will be exported said tom mayr owner of the mayr brothers 
mill in hoquiam wash mayr has been reduced to counting his supply 
in months instead of years while watching a stream of logs being 
loaded onto ships in grays harbor wash 
we want to put out logs to the highest value market in recent 
years the highest value has been offshore said jack taylor 
operations manager for weyerhaeuser in coos bay where the regions 
leading exporter of raw logs has started a new mill to produce 
metricdimension lumber for the japanese homebuilding market 
companies can generally get 25 percent more for export logs than 
they can in the domestic market said forest service economist don 
flora in seattle 
boomandbust cycles were known to the timber industry before the 
spotted owl entered the spotlight but for the first time the pinch 
is from a shortage of logs rather than rising mortgage rates and 
dips in the housing market 
eighteen years ago brad wentworth stopped off in the coastal 
town of gold beach to see some friends on his way to college to 
study forest management now hes 37 a husband and father and one 
of the 300 workers at gold beach plywood who will be out of a job 
this summer when the mill shuts down 
i got sucked into the mill because it was such good wages 
wentworth said i kick myself in the butt now 
thirteen other wood products mills in oregon and washington have 
closed this year putting nearly 2000 people out of work as the 
industry enters a new era of highpriced timber in short supply a 
referendum tuesday in oregon calls for a ban on exporting 
stategrown logs and asks congress to make permanent an annually 
renewed ban on exporting logs grown on federal land 
the mill is old and inefficient said gold beach mill manager 
eric saunders it would take about 3 million to bring it up why 
should we put in that kind of investment without knowing there is a 
stable supply of timber 
the shortage of timber doesnt come as a surprise but its 
magnitude does 
in 1976 oregon state university forestry professor john beuter 
reported that little mature timber was left on private land and that 
the industry would have to depend on national forests home to most 
of the oldgrowth timber to make it to the next century when 
secondgrowth trees planted before world war ii would be ready for 
harvest 
jerry hamilton director of resource services for seattles 
simpson timber co had expected harvests in national forests to 
decline about 20 percent in oregon and washington this year as the 
forest service revised its longrange management plans he now fears 
it could drop 50 percent because oldgrowth forests have been ruled 
offlimits because of the spotted owl 
historically a lot of the impetus for the management of 
federal lands in the west was to settle the west and develop it 
said beuter now a consultant in portland we are sort of at the 
end of that era now we are at the point of recognizing that cutting 
more timber isnt going to create new cities and new economic 
opportunity in the west in fact we are coming around to where 
saving the forests may create new economic opportunity 
ed whitelaw a university of oregon economics professor has been 
a leading proponent of the idea that the northwest has more to gain 
from preserving its blue skies green forests and clear water than 
from exploiting its resources 
most oregonians receive two paychecks he said one is in 
dollars the other comes from the environment by accounting for all 
other amenities i estimate that the environmental paycheck is worth 
13 billion the paycheck from the timber industry is 15 
billion 
in 1988 oregon and washington national forests supplied 54 
billion board feet of timber a third of the regions total harvest 
from all lands where the forest service management plans used in 
the 1980s allowed the annual harvest of 55 billion board feet the 
limit in the 1990s will be closer to 47 billion 
unlike owners of private forests the forest service by law may 
cut no more timber than it can grow back it also has to provide for 
the needs of fish wildlife campers hikers and water quality 
where it once had to answer only to the timber industry the 
service now has a crowd of watchdogs panting over its shoulder the 
governors of washington and oregon want to be sure there is enough 
timber to sustain the rural economy environmental groups demand 
preservation of oldgrowth forests academics have started offering 
new management techniques that follow the lead of nature and there 
is new unrest inside the forest service 
jeff debonis a willamette national forest timber sale planner 
has organized the association of forest service employees for 
environmental ethics with a mailing list of about 200 debonis 
wrote in february to forest service chief dale robertson claiming 
the agency is in bed with the industry 
the question we need to ask concerned citizens is why should 
the national forests be sacrificed to an overzealous and greedy 
industry that liquidated their own lands to make a fast cut he 
said 
robertsons staff is preparing a detailed response to debonis 
letter said spokeswoman rose narlock in washington dc maybe we 
need some of these things talked about it was a gutsy move on his 
part 
robertson has acknowledged that the forest service has taken a 
beating in the courts under the national environmental policy act 
evidence debonis cites for his argument that too many trees are 
being cut 
while loggers tie yellow ribbons to their trucks and demand more 
timber the grim truth is jobs are disappearing spotted owl or no 
spotted owl 
the biggest source of change in employment has been the 
modernization and automation of the forest products industry said 
wilderness society economist jeffrey t olson who produced a study 
concluding the decline in timber jobs in the northwest has little to 
do with cutting old growth in national forests 
flora the forest service economist said in the 1970s he figured 
each 1 million board feet of timber translated into eight timber 
jobs thats now down to 15 jobs in the hightech mills and four to 
five jobs overall 
timber is virtually extinct as a factor in the economies of 
portland and seattle but still vital in small cities and towns that 
grew up with it 
oregons 68700 woodproducts jobs almost all of them outside 
the portland area account for 52 percent of the states 
employment washingtons 41800 timber jobs account for 21 percent 
of its employment in 1986 the most recent figures available 
timber accounted for just 6 percent of oregons gross state product 
at 25 billion and 22 percent of washingtons at 16 billion 
but forest service economist con schallau in corvallis argues 
timber has a greater impact than that because it accounts for 38 
percent of oregons basic economy bringing in outside dollars 
and 18 percent of washingtons 
while economists may differ over timbers importance they agree 
the places that will be hurt worst are towns like gold beach 
population 1500 with a payroll of 6 million from gold beach 
plywood 
if you live in a big city youve got a lot of choices 
wentworth said but if you live here youve got to work in the 
brush or the mill 
