<TEXT>
colombia has lived in bloodshed almost constantly 
since its founding in 1819 and these days the violence is laced with 
cocaine and common crime as well as ideology but while most of its 
south american neighbors struggle for economic survival colombia is 
striding forward even though it is again at war with itself this is 
one of a series of periodic reports by the associated press on the 
economic social and political turbulence that has turned south 
america into a continent in crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in a simultaneous struggle with 
guerrillas rightwing vigilantes drug smugglers and assassins 
colombia resolutely survives 
to an extent it even thrives 
the withering crossfire of violence invites predictions of 
national perdition but a country accustomed to decades of 
bloodletting goes about its politics and business 
in general terms the state not only functions it functions 
better every day said pierre gilodes director of the foreign 
ministrys institute for higher developmental studies 
we dont know if this is a paradox or if there is some 
relationship between what is happening in the country and the 
efficient functioning of the state 
in an interview with the associated press gilodes said he 
suspects a kind of perversely positive relationship exists 
the state is pushed to function well or it will collapse 
said gilodes a french expert contracted by the government to head 
the institute 
the actions of shadowy rightwing groups may help keep some 
dissent stifled he added 
the state can decide that salaries will go up less than the 
cost of living and no one protests 
unions that would or should raise their voices are under 
pressure from private groups that kill labor activists 
in addition he said leftist guerrilla and rightwing violence 
in the countryside is steadily driving both poor and welltodo to 
the cities to help fuel the more productive urbanbased industries 
with seed money and cheap labor 
colombias gross national product of about 42 billion grew 37 
percent last year lower than the recent annual average but enviable 
to most struggling latin american countries annual inflation is 28 
percent a fraction of that of neighboring nations 
new factories go up daily and with healthy tax revenues the 
government regularly builds new roads and launches other public 
works projects 
illegal cocaine earnings bring home an estimated 500 milllion to 
12 billion a year and is believed responsible for perhaps 
onefifth of the countrys eonomic growth last year 
but gilodes insists drugs can hardly be called the economic 
engine for a country whose 6 billion in legal yearly exports 
include coffee oil coal and an evermore diverse array of 
nontraditional products such as flowers he attributes the success 
to many years of prudent management of a sound freemarket 
economy 
on the political side preliminary campaigning for congressional 
and municipal elections next march and presidential balloting in may 
is already under way nobody expects any big hitches 
democracy is even broadening its base absenteeism at the polls 
is shrinking each year and the country recently celebrated the 
first anniversary of the election of the countrys 1009 mayors who 
used to be appointed all political and social camps declared the 
experiment a great success 
colombia also thrives culturally with nightly performances of 
plays symphonies and popular music for a people who love to dance 
and can easily distinguish the beat of an inland rumba from a 
coastal cumbia 
fueled by the works of latin americas most popular living 
novelist gabriel garcia marquez colombias book industry is 
booming a national poetry contest in the industrial city of 
medellin the dark heart of cocaine country drew an enthusiastic 
crowd of 7000 people a love poem won 
to a visitor the countrys troubles the machinegun fire and car 
bombs can seem nonexistent or distant or quickly absorbed in the 
bustle of an exuberant people like a grenade lobbed in thick jungle 
on may 27 on a major bogota thoroughfare 220 pounds of 
explosive went off as the chief of the countrys security police 
gen miguel maza marquez was passing in his car he was just 
bruised but seven passersby were mortally wounded 
within a few hours the rubble had been swept up and life was 
back to normal 
but then in colombia death is measured by the dozen 
killings this year totaled 9411 as of early june an average 60 
a day according to national police department statistics 
that is down from a daily average of 66 last year when killings 
totaled 24280 eight times the total of 2924 in california which 
has 28 million inhabitants to colombias 31 million most adult 
colombian males are said to die by the knife gun or garrotte 
most of the deaths are what police call common homicides 
unrelated to politics but among this years victims were 67 
politicians and 86 policemen in the last eight months the 
government insurance company has paid off death benefits to the 
families of 771 armed forces members and 15 court officials 
the police even keep a statistic for mass killings involving 
five or more victims there have been 34 so far this year with a 
total of 175 victims 
occasionally there is a sign that even expansive colombia is 
having trouble absorbing death in such big numbers 
in the community called palestina on the cauca river not far 
from the city of manizales authorities complained that the town 
graveyard cant handle all the unclaimed bulletriddled corpses 
being pulled from the river according to a dispatch in the bogota 
newpspaper la prensa it said 120 bodies had been found since late 
last year 
the countrys sources of violence are manifold 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a variety of leftist guerrilla organizations have been active in 
colombia since the late 1950s and are blamed for 660 deaths so far 
in 1989 their domain includes expanses of littlepatrolled and 
sparsely populated territory where they impose taxes and draft 
recruits 
they also are prone to kidnapping for ransom as are many common 
criminals nationwide an average of two kidnappings are reported to 
police each day 
the cocaine business which surged in the early 1980s when the 
american streets and parlors became its biggest customer makes a 
substantial contribution to the death toll in deals gone sour and 
struggles for power 
more recently a new and fearsome element of violence has reared 
up the rightwing death squad fed by cocaine money and linked to 
government security organs and a dark society of sicarios the 
spanish term for killers for hire 
its victims include not only leftist politicians and government 
investigators but ragged tramps homosexuals prostitutes and street 
urchins in a process euphemistically called social cleansing 
allegations abound that the highest spheres of government have 
been infiltrated bought off or terrified into at least reluctant 
compliance with the drug bosses wishes but the government 
dismisses such allegations 
to reinforce its argument it points to continued attempts to 
assassinate and intimidate top justice and police officials 
president virgilio barco repeatedly has called the narcotics 
traffickers and rightwing death squads dangerous enemies of the 
state and he contends that recent police actions have hurt them 
badly 
violence is a mortally wounded beast he declared after the 
carbomb attack on maza marquez which he characterized as the 
lashingout of an angry animal 
in a recent conversation with reporters barco said there are 
judases everywhere but that doesnt mean this is a corrupt country 
the government the armed forces the police are more prepared 
each day to control crime in this country he said 
about 30 percent of colombians endure poverty according to 
official estimates the poverty stands in sharp contrast to economic 
advancement a beggar outside an exclusive mens store in bogota or 
on the road to the caribbean resort city of cartagena where local 
and foreign tourists pack fivestar hotels and beaches a ragged 
peasant strips whats left on the bones of a cow killed by a motor 
vehicle 
such misery is said to feed the ranks of leftist guerrilla 
groups but the government also claims some progress on that front 
one major guerrilla organization the april 19 movement is 
engaged in direct talks with the government on how its members might 
lay down their arms and join the political process some other 
groups including the biggest the revolutionary armed forces of 
colombia have expressed an interest in joining what is called the 
peace process 
this represents a big change in guerrilla attitudes compared 
with the 1970s when they believed they could take power by force 
said carlos jaramillo a government political scientist 
jaramillo is an assistant to the presidential counsel on the 
peace process rafael pardo many colombians view the talks with 
skepticism but jaramillo insisted the time is ripe for an accord 
guerrillas have been frustrated in decades of effort to extend their 
control to important urban centers he said 
the guerrilla has been unable to change his marginal status 
he added 
jaramillo said that overall the violence in colombia gives the 
impression of intensifying 
youre always saying it cant get any worse and then 
something worse happens 
but he contended it must be viewed within the context of 
virtually constant bloodshed since the countrys founding in 1819 
the country has lived through periods of much worse violence 
he said 
from 1830 to the turn of the century colombia endured 50 bloody 
local or national conflicts and in a period called la 
violencia roughly from 1948 to 1959 victims of a largely rural 
conflict between the traditional liberal and conservative parties 
were counted by the truckload estimates of the total number of dead 
in that decade of violence range from 70000 to 300000 
jaramillo said he detects a new willingness in many sectors of 
the country to attack and defeat all sources of violence be they 
from the right or the left 
its as if weve said well now weve touched bottom he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
colombias powerful cocaine chieftans 
such as fabio ochoa gonzalo rodriguez gacha and pablo escobar 
gaviria are known by name all across the country yet they remain 
at large seemingly immune from arrest and prosecution 
despite heavy us pressure for their capture and extradition on 
smuggling charges the biggest often seem to slip away from any 
attempt to capture and hold them 
they are said to pay informants in security forces and the 
courts those they cannot bribe they try to intimidate with death 
threats that are not idle their victims include justice minister 
rodrigo lara bonilla killed in 1984 and attorney general carlos 
hoyos assassinated last year 
in an interview colombias national police chief maj gen 
miguel gomez badilla said he receives threats daily by mail and 
telephone but insists the forces of order and justice are not cowed 
he said the drug bosses are being aggressively persecuted if not 
prosecuted 
escobar gacha ochoa these people are fugitives they are 
being hunted gomez said 
while they are in their own territory its hard to catch them 
why because there are many people who make their living off them 
and who protect them 
but remember there was a time when pablo escobar was 
considered a robin hood in certain sections of medellin where he 
financed housing churches recreation areas gomez said he cant 
do that anymore he has to hide 
gomez formerly chief of the forces antinarcotics division is 
considered a top name on the hitlist of the cocaine smugglers and 
rightwing death squads he is constantly accompanied by heavily 
armed bodyguards and his wifes and five childrens movements are 
restricted 
he also faces an internal enemy the ranks of his 80000member 
force have been aggressively purged with 1353 policemen expelled 
in the last 18 months for alleged links to narcotics or the 
private justice groups as the death squads call themselves 
i cant deny that there are police linked to narcotics 
trafficking but we are uncovering them gomez said 
he added that said secuirity forces had delivered several 
decisive blows in recent months to the cocaine cartels and death 
squads in one case dismantling a lab that held 11000 pounds of the 
powder and striking at several training camps for hired gunmen 
at the camps authorities find hefty arsenals of the latest in 
weaponry including rocket and grenade launchers shiny new assault 
rifles automatic pistols silencers to police and the military it 
is a fearsome byproduct of the drug industry 
the cocaine goes out of the country and the profits return in 
the form of weapons which can be sold at five or ten times their 
purchase price gomez said 
he said the government of president virgilio barco however has 
increased spending on sophisticated equipment for the armed forces 
and police 
the united states has helped with 10 million in antinarcotics 
aid and feels it is getting its moneys worth 
were getting more blast for our buck here than in any other 
country in latin america said a locally assigned us drug 
enforcement administration official speaking on condition he not be 
identified by name 
