<TEXT>
she was once an enfant terrible of modern dance 
and later became one of the most famous choreographers to emerge 
from avantgarde dance today twyla tharp is a little more 
traditonal she works for a ballet company im an oldwest 
pioneer type person you just have to examine where your fences are 
built i have no fences i have open spaces i dont like 
categorizing people or dancing except into good or bad the 
48yearold choreographer says 
tharp who choreographed for her own modern dance company and the 
movies hair ragtime amadeus and white nights 
joined american ballet theater last summer and never one to move 
in mincing steps she presented three new dances on the same night 
during ballet theaters current season at the metropolitan opera 
i like setting new challenges for myself she said in an 
interview the work has all been done since august with the paris 
opera ballet thrown in 
the choreographer dissolved twyla tharp dance last july and she 
and eight or nine dancers about half her troupe joined abt i 
wouldnt have disbanded and not worked she says you never go 
from somewhere to nowhere 
the reason for giving up her own company she says was economic 
the company was very well run we didnt have a deficit we had 
done over six months of touring a year for two years in a row not 
many dancers were enthusiastic about that my fundraising became 
more and more a concern i had less and less time in a studio new 
work wasnt happening 
she hasnt had a day off since august when youre working as 
hard as i am a day off doesnt help im willing to kill myself and 
everybody else to get it right but the work since august has been 
creating new ballets 
first she choreographed bums rush balletic vaudeville then 
worked on everlast presented like a 1920s musical comedy with 
the lively plot told in dance and three singers and a pianist 
onstage performing appropriate jerome kern songs she started 
quartet in neoclassical ballet style before she finished 
everlast 
when ballet theater took time off and before she finished 
quartet she created rules of the game for the paris opera 
ballet she flew back to the united states finished quartet 
flew back to paris and found her leading ballerina sylvie guillem 
had left the company for the british royal ballet so she rewrote 
world premieres kept her hopping quartet in chicago feb 4 
bums rush in chicago feb 8 rules of the game in paris 
feb 17 and everlast in san francisco march 2 
about differences between modern dance and ballet tharp is 
emphatic 
as far as im concerned theyre nonexistent since george 
balanchine made agon to me the determining factor is not whether 
the dancers are in bare feet it is the welding of dance tradition 
with innovational movement and concept and perception about what 
society is and how it functions she said i think there was not 
enough real choice being exerted by modern choreographers given 
that choice this whole issue disappeared 
she first choreographed for a ballet company in 1973 when she 
used beach boys recordings for the joffrey ballet a jazzy push 
comes to shove in 1976 was her first dance for mikhail 
baryshnikov now artistic director of ballet theater 
about everlast she says its a fully developed narrative 
it has a boxer who begins in love with the wrong girl and ends up 
with the right girl through the advice of several characters in the 
plot 
the jerome kern songs were around they were written for 
shows need a song where the ingenue falls for the guy here are 50 
of those it had to be the right one of the 50 in terms of how it 
registered in the overall flow of this piece 
both quartet to terry riley music and in the upper 
room which tharp choreographed for her own company in 1986 and 
which ballet theater danced here for the first time this season are 
plotless but for tharp nothing is really plotless 
balanchine thought there is a narrative in everything center 
stage is a different place than upstage left who appears in those 
places and at what time tells a story 
she said in the upper room isnt meant to be biblical its 
an abstract plot its about completion the way things reinforce 
one another growth and development 
whether audiences could verbalize what it means or not i dont 
think is important i think one of the reasons the piece is so 
popular is that people feel it makes a constructive and positive 
statement if you make an investment it will be returned in kind 
with interest 
in the upper room is set to philip glass music which tharp 
has been using for 20 years she wanted to call it glass and 
sometimes does in conversation but because jerome robbins 
choreogaphed glass pieces for the new york city ballet the 
composer chose a different name 
in rules of the game the dance she choreographed for the 
paris opera ballet the rules of the theatrical game was what i 
was attempting to express she said this season after some 
experiences id had i began to feel i understood some rules of some 
games i set about to build on them rather than avantgarde 
fashion start from nowhere 
she fought leaving the avantgarde she says but at a certain 
point you have to acknowledge ive learned some things and here 
they are 
the reason im interested in these rules of the game is theyve 
been lost to some degree since jerry robbins stopped working in 
theater young people dont know how to structure they dont have 
access to the rules the game hasnt been played in a very long time 
the avantgarde is everybody trying to be smarter than what 
works perfectly well a lot of the time i went through it as long 
as possible 
a piece looking avantgarde never has been my concern my 
concern has always been to do something of quality that would have 
some impact if it stayed around or influenced something ive 
never been one just for shock value 
