<TEXT>
time inc has begun its campaign to woo 
shareholders away from an unsolicited 107 billion takeover bid 
from paramount communications inc and win their support for times 
14 billion tender offer for warner communications inc 
basically times tack is to tell shareholders the instant 
gratification that paramounts 175ashare allcash bid offers is 
an illusion and that theyll profit more in the long run by holding 
on to their stock and allowing the timewarner merger to go through 
time took its campaign to the shareholders in a letter released 
to the press saturday the media giant spelled out the reasons why 
its board rejected the paramount bid and amended the terms of its 
earlier stockswap merger agreement with warner to include a 
70ashare offer for warner 
the letter which essentially reiterated points time officials 
made in statements and interviews friday told shareholders that 
paramounts offer was highly conditional and subject to many 
uncertainties including obtaining the necessary 14 billion of 
financing and all required regulatory approvals 
the company repeated its estimate that it would take as long as a 
year for paramount to win the approvals required from about 800 
cable television systems for which time now holds franchises that 
would delay the completion of paramounts bid and consequently 
payments to time shareholders for their stock 
time is making the franchises a key part of its strategy time 
president nicholas j nicholas jr led off an interview friday by 
zeroing in on the cable operations and warning further that 
paramount wont get financing if it doesnt win title to times 
assets including the cable operations 
times cable tv arm american television and communications corp 
of stamford conn said sunday that it had filed a lawsuit seeking 
to block paramounts tender offer unless paramount first gains 
approval for the transfer of all of atcs cable system franchises 
the connecticut superior court suit claims that paramounts bid 
to acquire time stock through a trust could violate the terms of a 
large majority of atcs 767 local cable tv franchises agreements 
thereby invalidating them 
the agreements would be invalidated because their terms state 
that ownership of the franchises cannot change hands without the 
approval of the municipalities or other agencies that granted them 
the suit says 
in a response sunday paramount said this is another 
diversionary suit without substance we are going to move promptly 
to dismiss it 
in its shareholder letter and an accompanying securities and 
exchange commission filing time charged that the terms of 
paramounts financing have not been determined or negotiated 
paramount said it remained confident the conditions will be 
satisfied with reasonable promptness and said it would continue to 
pursue time nicholas who under the timewarner proposal will 
eventually be chairman of the combined companies said time 
officials expected the unwanted suitor to raise its bid 
but even if paramount does put more money on the table time will 
keep reminding stockholders of the conditions that will still be 
attached to the bid and it will keep talking about the future of 
time and warner 
times letter said shareholders ultimately would benefit from the 
creation of timewarner inc because the price of their time stock 
would rise after the merger reflecting the assets and cash flow of 
both companies 
time stockholders would have an opportunity to share in the 
higher values expected from the pursuit of times longterm 
strategic objective to become a worldwide media and entertainment 
company the letter said 
shareholders of both time and warner had been scheduled to vote 
friday on the original merger proposal but time said the meeting 
would be adjourned until june 30 and that shareholders would vote 
only on the election of directors and other matters not related to 
the merger 
time said the early returns of proxies mailed in connection with 
the original agreement strongly supported the timewarner 
combination however many of these proxies likely were received 
before paramount announced its 175pershare cash bid on june 6 
time outlined on friday a twostage offer under which it would 
pay 70 a share in cash for 100 million warner shares in a tender 
offer and then exchange 70 a share in cash and securities for the 
remaining 100 million shares of warner stock 
a merger of time and warner would drive up the cost of acquiring 
the company the acquisition of warner also would increase times 
debt load and make it less attractive to wouldbe bidders 
under the agreement announced in march time stockholders would 
have received a share in the new company timewarner inc for each 
time share while warner shareholders would get 0465 of a share of 
the new company for each of their warner shares 
time conceded in its letter that the original timewarner merger 
plan had accounting and financial advantages because it involved an 
exchange of stock that would be lost under the new proposal 
but time officials said the company would issue fewer or no new 
shares after the merger giving each existing time share a greater 
proportion of timewarners assets and cash flow 
