<TEXT>
ford motor co will increase the overseas content 
of two large cars while putting more domestic parts in two small 
vehicles to meet a more stringent federal fuel economy standard an 
official said monday 
as a result the larger cars will be reclassified as imports in 
federal fuel economy calculations while the smaller cars now listed 
as imports will be counted as domestic 
the reclassifications will be made despite the fact that the 
large cars are assembled in ontario not considered foreign for 
carclassification purposes and that one of the small cars is made 
in mexico said joel pitcoff of the automakers research staff 
ford will reduce the share of north americanmade components in 
the ford crown victoria and mercury grand marquis from about 90 
percent to just under 75 percent pitcoff said 
the change which will occur early in 1991 will be offset by an 
increase in the north american content of the smaller ford probe and 
mercury tracer so that both qualify as domestic vehicles even 
though the tracer is assembled in mexico pitcoff said 
the net domestic content of the four vehicles will be higher 
than it is today pitcoff said he said less than half of the 
content of the two smaller models now comes from north american 
sources 
ford is selling crown victorias and grand marquis at a rate of 
225000250000 a year about the same as the total for the probe 
and tracer he said 
under a 1975 federal law automakers will be required to have a 
corporate average fuel economy of 275 miles per gallon for the 1990 
model year the transportation department now holds producers to a 
265 mpg standard 
the socalled cafe standard has different requirements for 
domestically made cars those with at least 75 percent north 
american content and cars imported under the companys name plates 
with fewer than 75 percent north american parts 
ford now barely meets the fuel economy standard for domestically 
made cars with a 266 mpg average but safely exceeds it for imports 
at about 32 mpg pitcoff said 
a united auto workers spokesman at the unions convention in 
anaheim calif criticized fords moves 
the uaw continues to be concerned about jobs for us 
workers said the spokesman who spoke on the condition of 
anonymity domestic manufacturers have trouble meeting cafe 
standards because they import far too many small cars now they 
propose to import big cars as well 
we are concerned that this will further erode the jobs of our 
members 
the next generation of the crown victoria and grand marquis is 
scheduled to go into production in early 1991 in st thomas 
ontario the probe is built for ford by mazda motor corp at its 
flat rock plant south of detroit while the tracer is assembled in 
hermosillo mexico 
sales leader general motors corp like no 2 ford is struggling 
to comply with current fuel economy standards and says it will have 
trouble meeting the higher 1990 standard no 3 chrysler corp sells 
fewer large fuelhungry cars and hasnt faced any difficulty 
meeting the cafe limits 
</TEXT>
