when you consider the expansion over the weekend i find it 
hard to believe that its ending 
the unauthorized walkouts began last week after a umw rally in 
charleston to protest pittstons failure to sign a nationwide 
contract and to protest fines and jail terms assessed against union 
members in virginia 
pittston wants its own contract that would include mandatory 
overtime sunday work and a cut in pension benefits the umw insists 
that the company sign the national contract which would require 
pittston to pay into the national pension fund and keep mines closed 
on sundays 
about 1600 umw employees walked off their pittston jobs in 
virginia and west virginia on april 5 after working more than 14 
months without a contract the strike spread to pittstons kentucky 
operations monday idling an additional 200 umw members 
pittston last week declared negotiations at an impasse which 
allowed it to implement its latest contract offer umw leaders are 
required by law to present that offer to their membership 
eight people were arrested monday in alexandria va after 
sympathizers of the striking miners snarled commuter traffic headed 
into the nations capital where the umw is based the protesters 
allegedly traveled two or three cars abreast at speeds of 5 mph on 
highways heading into washington from northern virginia according 
to virginia state police spokeswoman lucy caldwell 
police spotted about 100 sympathizers most of whom had signs in 
their car windows or displayed umw flags on their radio antennas 
caldwell said 
the more than 27000 miners off work monday included 16000 in 
west virginia 3900 in alabama 2500 in pennsylvania 1750 in 
indiana 1270 in kentucky 1100 in ohio 650 in illinois 338 in 
missouri and 200 in tennessee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890619-0305 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
northwest airlines parent nwa inc accepted 
a 4 billion buyout offer monday from a group led by los angeles 
investor alfred checchi capping a weekslong bidding war and taking 
further steps to keep other bidders from returning 
the checchi group which agreed to pay 121 a share for the 
parent of the nations fourthlargest airline said it planned to 
retain current management and believed it could win needed federal 
approval of the sale 
nwa announced that if its deal fell through with the checchi 
group which included klm royal dutch airlines and the australian 
conglomerate elders ixl it would undertake a recapitalization that 
would pay nwa shareholders a special 70 a share cash dividend 
analysts said such a recapitalization which would load nwa up 
with new debt and possibly place a big stock holding into friendly 
hands would make the company much less attractive to hostile 
suitors 
nwa stock soared 650 a share to 11412 on the new york stock 
exchange 
the checchi group wings holdings inc beat at least three other 
bidders rival airline pan am corp the international association 
of machinists which represents about 20000 of northwests 37000 
workers and oil billionaire marvin davis who sparked the bidding 
with a 90 a share offer on march 28 
davis who owns 29 percent of nwas common shares said in a 
statement that he supports the proposed transaction but will 
reserve final judgement until he meets with his advisers 
while disappointed by the outcome i am pleased that the nwa 
special committee has elected to sell the company as we urged all 
along davis said 
pan am issued a statement saying it was disappointed its bid was 
not chosen but that it wanted its offer to be considered if the 
checchi bid fell through and before nwa undertook its 
recapitalization plan 
the machinists union did not return repeated phone calls seeking 
comment 
checchi 41 a former marriott corp treasurer said he signed an 
agreement with the nwa board about 1 am monday in a new york city 
law office 
northwest said the checchi bid was the highest offer it received 
had the fewest contingencies and was the most likely to close 
checchi said none of his associates would join northwests 
management team and he expected nwa chairman steven rothmeier to 
keep running the company 
i talked to steve last night and we mutually congratulated each 
other checchi said monday i certainly hope he plans on 
staying i have no reason to believe he is not 
checchis proposal includes 700 million equity and 335 billion 
to be borrowed from a syndicate of banks led by bankers trust co 
checchis equity partners include klm bankers trust richard c 
blum and associates a san francisco merchant banking and investment 
firm and elders finance group a subsidiary of elders ixl 
with about 305 million common shares outstanding the tender 
offer would cost about 37 billion but checchis group already 
owns 49 percent of nwa stock the buyers also are contributing 
equity that boosts the total package to over 4 billion 
the buyout was conditioned on a majority of nwas shares being 
purchased and the deal being completed by sept 18 
checchi said he was not concerned about meeting financial fitness 
requirements of the us transportation department which must 
approve the acquisition 
the justice department is not likely to review the deal because 
it does not involve a merger of two airlines a department spokesman 
said 
federal regulations prohibit foreign carriers such as klm from 
owning more than 25 percent of a us carrier 
however klm and northwest could share gates and coordinate 
schedules for connecting flights said barbara beyer of avmark inc 
an aviation consulting firm in arlington va such an arrangement 
would not require any merger of employees or corporate staff she 
said 
checchi said his plan calls for substantial growth at 
northwest including the purchase of 138 new planes already on order 
or option by nwa 
william genoese president of the airline division of the 
international brotherhood of teamsters said he would meet with 
checchis group later this week 
they want the company to grow said genoese whose union 
represents about 7000 flight attendants and clerks at northwest 
im for anyone that comes in that will make things grow and 
improve labor relations 
nwa said its recapitalization plan would pay shareholders 70 
cash per share which would cost about 21 billion the plan might 
be financed partly with an equity contribution from a third party 
nwa said which would determine how much the company would have to 
borrow to pay for the recapitalization 
kurt rivard an analyst for dain bosworth inc of minneapolis 
said new debt the recapitalization would load on nwa could 
discourage a hostile bidder from trying to circumvent the checchi 
deal 
mondays decision capped a bidding war opened march 28 by davis 
who offered 27 billion or 90 a share 
the board rejected davis bid and his subsequent tender offer for 
the same amount it then opened a twophase bidding process that 
attracted other suitors such as pan am 
however nwas board rejected the first round of bids as 
inadequate and invited suitors to try again 
</TEXT>
